please explain the calculator, where does the wasted jours per week come from?

The "Wasted Hours" metric in your calculator represents administrative overhead and redundant manual tasks that AI is specifically designed to eliminate. In a professional pitch, you can explain that this isn't about employees being lazy; it‚Äôs about "work about work."

Here is the breakdown of where those numbers come from and how the math works:

1. Where do the "Wasted Hours" come from?

Industry benchmarks (from McKinsey, Slack, and Workfront) show that the average knowledge worker spends up to 60% of their day on tasks that are not their primary job. Common "wasted" tasks include:

  • Searching for information: Digging through emails, Teams, or Drive to find a specific document (Custom Agents/Gems solve this).

  • Manual Data Entry: Copying information between different software suites.

  • Meeting Coordination/Summaries: Writing up notes and action items (Copilot/Gemini automates this).

  • Routine Emails: Drafting standard responses or follow-ups.

The Logic: Even at a conservative estimate of 5 hours per week, you are only assuming that an employee spends one hour per day on these automatable tasks. This makes your pitch look realistic and grounded rather than "too good to be true."

2. How the Calculator Works (The Formula)

The app uses a standard Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) formula tailored for the Canadian market:

  • Average Hourly Wage ($45): This is a balanced average for Canadian professional services (Accounting, Legal, IT) when you include benefits and overhead.

  • Annual Loss Calculation: [Team Size] √ó [Hours Wasted/Week] √ó 52 Weeks √ó $45/hour

  • Potential Savings (35%): We apply a 35% Efficiency Gain factor. This is based on Microsoft's own "Copilot for Work" studies, which found that users were 29% faster at specific tasks and saved significant time on administrative work.

3. Why this helps your BDC Pitch

When the BDC officer sees this, you are shifting the conversation from "AI is a cool gadget" to "AI is a financial necessity." You are showing them that a company with 15 employees is likely losing over $175,000 every year simply because their network isn't hardened and their workflows aren't automated.

Your brand gets broken when your market and your brand evolve at different rates. This is what creates a misalignment in perceptions.

For example, your company may consider itself a market leader in expert knowledge and professionalism. You know you‚Äôre a good fit for your target customers, but your brand is sending altogether different signals. In fact, your customers perceive you as inaccessible and confusing.

If you‚Äôre suffering from this kind of misalignment, I want you to remember a broken brand is not a permanent state. Companies evolve. Customers evolve. Cultures evolve. It happens.

How do you know if your brand is broken?

Here are three common signs of a broken (or breaking) brand.

1. Your brand has become reactive

You respond to product launches, competitor moves and other market opportunities ad hoc and reactively. As a brand, you often go off on tangents to ‚Äòexplore‚Äô new opportunities that take you away from what you originally started out to achieve.

2. Your brand has become outdated

Your brand is stale and perceived as boring. There used to be a lot of great customer buzz about your business, but now you no longer resonate the way you used to.

3. Your reputation has been damaged

Your brand is being viewed in a negative light by your customers. You‚Äôve made some changes to address this, but you seem to continue to lose new customers as well as previously loyal ones.

So how do you fix it?

If you think your company‚Äôs brand is broken, here are some steps you can take to get back on track.

1. Establish a solid foundation

You must invest time with your leadership team to develop or redefine your core brand statements (brand vision, value proposition and positioning statement) and identify the market segments you are targeting. In order to align brand with market perceptions, you need to develop a detailed understanding of both sides of the equation.

Often with broken brands, it‚Äôs slight variances in how these fundamental elements are understood within the company that create the initial cracks. Invest time with your leadership team to clearly redefine what your brand represents and what it‚Äôs growing into.

2. Facilitate your brand culture

It‚Äôs one thing to have your brand documented on paper, it‚Äôs another to bring it to life. Demonstrating your brand value to the market is also known as your brand personality‚Äîwith emphasis on the personality. That all starts with people.

Your people are the ones working for your company, demonstrating your brand on a daily basis. A customer service rep who is genuinely excited to help and enthusiastic about her work creates a different brand perception than one who is bored and uninterested.

Your people are also your customers‚Äîthe ones who buy from you, the ones who are just discovering you and even the ones who choose to no longer do business with you.

People create culture. Build your brand based on the culture that exists or encourage your culture to evolve with your brand (or, better yet, do both!). Think of WestJet. Whether you‚Äôre a staff member or a customer, the brand is a culture of WestJetters and your interaction with the company makes you part of that crew.

3. Create a consistent customer experience

Brand personality covers all manner of customer experience, from the language and tone of your messaging to customer service response times to sales conversion efforts and everything in between.

Every interaction with your company is a demonstration of brand behaviour and part of creating your customer experience. Again, your goal is to align customer perceptions of your brand with the way your organization wants to be perceived. To achieve this, you have to speak with one voice throughout the customer experience. So, from our previous example‚Äîthe ideal brand is one where you‚Äôre aligning your customers‚Äô need to have an accessible, simplified understanding of what you do with your company‚Äôs need to demonstrate your expertise and leadership in your field.

Again, a brand that‚Äôs broken is not locked in that destiny. Rebuilding your brand is a matter of realignment. Get started by setting a strong foundation that will allow your brand to grow and evolve with your market.

What is a competitive analysis?

A competitive analysis is an assessment of your competitors‚Äô products, services and sales tactics, evaluating their strengths and weaknesses relative to your own. It‚Äôs good business practice to conduct a full competitive analysis at least once a year.

‚ÄúYou always want to stay on top of what your competitors are doing and where you stand,‚Äù Kazim says. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs something to make part of your organizational discipline, like keeping good books.‚Äù

What is the purpose of a competitive analysis?

A competitive analysis will help you see your own unique advantages as well as any potential barriers to growth so you can strengthen your marketing and business strategies. It also keeps your business proactive instead of reactive. Many entrepreneurs operate based on preconceived ideas about their competitors and market landscape, but those ideas may not be accurate or may be out of date.

‚ÄúChallenge your assumptions because the data changes all the time,‚Äù Kazim says. ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt wait until a competitor launches a new product before changing your strategy, otherwise you might end up in a reactive position to market changes. You want to be proactive‚Äîand it‚Äôs easier to be proactive if you do this exercise regularly.‚Äù

How to conduct a competitive analysis in 5 steps

A competitive analysis involves four key steps:

1. Identify your competitors

This sounds straightforward, but in fact there are different kinds of competitors to consider. They include:

Direct competitors: These are the businesses that offer similar products and services and target the same customers in the geographic area that your business serves.

Secondary/indirect competitors: These are the businesses that offer different products and services and target a different clientele, but are in your same general category (e.g., a winery and a brewery are secondary competitors because they both sell alcohol).

Substitute competitors: These are businesses that offer different products and services but target the same customers in your geographic area.

‚ÄúFor an in-person business like a nail salon, home nail kits are an example of substitute competition,‚Äù Kazim explains. ‚ÄúDuring the pandemic, people got used to doing their nails at home. That likely encroached on a lot of salons‚Äô business.‚Äù

Sometimes it‚Äôs not obvious who your competitors are. In those cases, Kazim recommends using the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS).

With NAICS, every kind of business in Canada is given a six-digit code‚Äîfrom toy stores (NAICS 451120) to tax preparation services (NAICS 541213). You can search the NAICS website by keyword to find the code for your business type. Then you can search for Statistics Canada data tables related to your NAICS code to find information such as average company size, operating expenses and employee wages for your industry. That helps paint a picture of how your business stacks up relative to the rest of your field.

‚ÄúThose benchmarks can give you some interesting insights,‚Äù says Kazim. ‚ÄúYou might realize you‚Äôre not investing as much in marketing as others in your industry, for example, or your wage costs are way above average.‚Äù

2. Gather information about your competitors

Once you‚Äôve identified your competitors, evaluate them in terms of the ‚Äúfour Ps‚Äù of the marketing mix:

Product: Compare their products to your own, ideally by purchasing and trying them out yourself. How is the quality? What features do you like or dislike?

Pricing: How are their products and services priced? Do their prices vary for channel partners and customers? What is their discount policy? Can you estimate their cost structure?

Place: What is their geographic reach or service area compared to your business?

Promotion: What marketing tactics are they using to interact and engage with their customers? What is their presence on social media?

The concept of the ‚Äúfour Ps‚Äù has evolved since its invention, so be sure to look at other factors as well, including:

Positioning: Review their websites, social media, product documents, brochures and catalogues. Who are their target markets? What is their unique selling proposition?

Reputation: What are people saying about your competitors‚Äô products and services online and on social media? How do the reviews compare to those for your business?

People: How big is their organization? What is the general profile of the people they employ?

Partnerships: Who are their suppliers? How long have they been working together?

If you‚Äôve never done this exercise before, Kazim recommends spending a couple of weeks with your sales, marketing and customer service teams to collect the data and do the research. Then, sit down with your team for a focused two-hour session to walk through what you‚Äôve found and map out the results.

In addition to the thorough annual analysis, Kazim says it‚Äôs useful to set aside some time every couple of months to do a quick refresh of the data‚Äîto ensure you‚Äôre always staying proactive instead of reactive.

3. Analyze your competitors‚Äô strengths and weaknesses

During the two-hour session with your team, it‚Äôs important that you can easily compare the performance of your competitors with your own. Start by ranking your competitors in the criteria listed above on a scale from 1 to 10, suggests Kazim, using a simple grid/table like the one below:

Example of a competitive analysis table

Enlarge the image

Next, prepare a written evaluation of each competitor‚Äôs respective strengths and weaknesses. For example, are they popular because of their location? Visibility? Quality of their staff? Are their prices too high? Does their product lack a key feature demanded by customers?

Summarize everything that would make a consumer choose (or not choose) each competitor.

4. Determine your competitive advantage

With all the information at your fingertips, it‚Äôs time to figure out what the results mean for your business strategy.

‚ÄúAsk yourself: what are we good at relative to the competition and where do we want to focus?‚Äù says Kazim. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a little bit of a ‚Äòwho do you want to be when you grow up?‚Äô kind of question.‚Äù

Analyzing the competitive landscape will help pinpoint your competitive advantage. It could be a distinctive strength that appeals to your target market and something you can build your brand image and messaging around. Or if you see a weakness in the competition, you could lower your prices and launch new promotions to take advantage of the opportunity.

That said, while it‚Äôs important to keep tabs on the competition and improve your business in response, Kazim says you shouldn‚Äôt allow concerns about what others are doing to fully dictate or dominate your strategy.

If you‚Äôre the only nail shop in your small town, keep an eye on what is happening with the nail shop in next town over and see how you measure up.

Mallika Kazim

Senior Business Advisor, BDC Advisory Services

Further tips for conducting a competitive analysis

If you‚Äôre conducting your first competitive analysis, don‚Äôt worry about being perfectly accurate or drilling down in minute detail. It‚Äôs more important to get an actionable sense of the competitive landscape and the general patterns shaping your market, says Kazim. She also encourages taking a holistic perspective.

‚ÄúMany entrepreneurs tend to focus only on pricing and products,‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúBut you need to look at everything that affects where your competitors stand in the market: how their customers are changing, whether they‚Äôre investing in their businesses and so on. Forming a complete picture of your competitors gives you that much more decision-making insight.‚Äù

Ideally, your analysis will feature at least one or two direct competitors in the mix. But what if there are no direct competitors in your immediate geographic service area? This can be an issue for many smaller entrepreneurs, especially if they have a very niche product or service. In this case, you can still do a competitive analysis‚Äîyou‚Äôll just need to think outside the box and look more closely at the substitute competitors who might ‚Äústeal wallet share‚Äù from your customers. You can also look to other cities or regions to get a comparative benchmark.

‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre the only nail shop in your small town, keep an eye on what is happening with the nail shop in the next town over and see how you measure up,‚Äù Kazim advises.

What‚Äôs next?

By seeing how the results of your competitive analysis fit with your business strategy, you may identify new areas of opportunity: a ‚Äúsweet spot‚Äù you can take over or a gap you can fill to take your business to the next level.

Detailed information for 2023

Frequency:

The annual multifactor productivity program breaks down the growth in labour productivity into its key determinants: capital intensity (or changes in the amount of capital per hour worked), investment in human capital, and multifactor productivity which includes technological change, organizational innovation and economies of scale.

Data release - April 7, 2025 (Multifactor productivity growth estimates and industry productivity database); April 14, 2025 (Estimates of multifactor productivity growth in the provinces)

Description

Data sources and methodology

Data accuracy

Documentation

Description

Productivity measures the efficiency with which resources are employed in economic activity. Annual productivities series are widely watched by analysts, government policymakers and researchers to quantify the extent to which productivity contributes to economic growth and the standards of living over the long run.

Statistical activity

The Canadian Productivity Accounts (CPA) are responsible for producing, analyzing and disseminating Statistics Canada's official data on productivity and for the production and integration of data on employment, hours worked and capital services consistent with the System of National Economic Accounts. To this end, the CPA comprises three programs. The quarterly program provides current estimates on labour productivity and labour costs at the aggregate level for 15 industry groups. The annual multifactor productivity program provides yearly estimates on multifactor productivity and related measures (output, capital input, labour input and intermediate inputs) as they apply to the major sectors of the economy and to industries at the national and provincial levels (see Productivity Measures and Related Variables - National and Provincial [Annual], record number 1402). Lastly, the annual provincial program, as an integral part of the provincial and territorial economic accounts, provides estimates of employment, hours worked, labour productivity and labour costs at the industry level for each province and territory (see Labour Productivity Measures - Provinces and Territories [Annual], record number 5103).

This information is highly relevant and provides a much more sophisticated "technical" anchor for your first validation point.

For a BDC loan officer, this shows you understand the macro-economic drivers the government uses to measure the health of the Canadian economy.
